    {
      "note_no": "40",
      "note": "Lit., \"which they will never [be able to] reach\" or \"fulfil\". This is a reference to the conceit which makes many agnostics think that man is \"self-sufficient\" and that, therefore, there are no limits to what he may yet achieve, and no need to assume that he is responsible to a higher Power. Cf. in this connection 96:6-7, which is one of the earliest Qur'anic revelations: \"Nay, verily, man becomes grossly overweening whenever he believes himself to be self-sufficient.\" And since this \"self-sufficiency\" is entirely illusory, those who build their world-view on it \"will never be able to satisfy their overweening conceit\". (Cf. also the reference to \"arrogant, self-exalting hearts\" in verse 35 above.)"
    }
  ],
  "en_snotes_yusuf": "The Disputes are actuated by nothing but the desire for self-glory and selfaggrandizement. Their desire is not likely to receive fruition, but others should take warning from it.",
